The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, February 14, 2004 				 Investment approvals jump 30% 
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 																								New Delhi, Feb. 13: The industrial investment climate in the country is looking up. Industrial entrepreneurs memoranda and letters of intent issued by the government show that approvals rose 30 per cent in 2003 over the previous year. 																								The total investment under these approvals is expected to touch the Rs 120,000-crore mark in 2003 compared with Rs 91,940 crore in 2002.																								The rise in investment has also been noticed in the quarter-on-quarter figures for the year, an official statement said.																								The growth in investment is also reflected by other indicators like sanctions and disbursements by financial institutions, non-food credit extended by scheduled commercial banks and private placements by Indian companies. 																								Sanctions by financial institutions were pegged at Rs 27,500 crore  a 185 per cent increase over the previous year. Similarly, disbursements during this period were at Rs 15,700 crore which is 72 per cent higher than the corresponding figure of the previous year.
